 Osiris is part of the ancient Egyptian religious system, specifically associated with the afterlife, the underworld, and the dead. He is identified as a god of transition, resurrection, and regeneration. As "King of the Living" and "Foremost of the Westerners," he holds kingship over the land of the dead. His role aligns with the broader conceptual framework of the Egyptian afterlife and the processes of death, burial, resurrection, and the cyclical nature of life. Additionally, through syncretism, he is linked with the moon god Iah, further integrating him into the wider Egyptian religious tradition.
